## The Hypocrites (71-91, 138-145)

They come up again. The tone is harsher here than in Al-Baqarah.

In Medina, the hypocrites were a constant political problem. They claimed to be Muslim but actively undermined the community. When the Muslims were called to fight, they dragged their feet. When Muslims suffered losses, they said *"Didn't we tell you?"* When things went well, they claimed to have always been on board.

> *"They want you to disbelieve as they have disbelieved, so that you would be alike."* (89)

The surah calls them out for sitting comfortably while others sacrifice. But even here, exceptions are made:

> *"Except for those who take refuge with a people between whom and you there is a treaty, or those who come to you with hearts unwilling to fight you or fight their own people."* (90)

If someone genuinely doesn't want to fight and seeks peace, that's accepted. The anger is directed at those who *pretend* to be with the Muslims while working against them.

