## Fighting and Migration (74-100)

The surah pushes back against those who refuse to fight when the cause is defending the oppressed:

> *"And what is wrong with you that you do not fight in the cause of God and for the oppressed among men, women, and children who say: Our Lord, take us out of this city of oppressive people?"* (75)

These "oppressed" were Muslims still trapped in Mecca, unable to leave, being persecuted. The Quran is asking: how can you sit comfortably in Medina while your people suffer?

---

**Migration** (hijra) is a major theme. Those who left everything behind in Mecca and migrated to Medina are honored. Those who *could* leave but chose to stay, without a valid excuse, are questioned:

> *"When the angels take the souls of those who have wronged themselves, they will ask: 'In what condition were you?' They will reply: 'We were oppressed in the land.' The angels will say: 'Was not the earth of God spacious enough for you to emigrate?'"* (97)

The message: if you're living under oppression and have the ability to leave, staying and accepting it is not an excuse.

But immediately after, an exemption:

> *"Except for the truly helpless among men, women, and children who have no means and no way out."* (98)

Those who genuinely *can't* leave are forgiven. The criticism is for those who *can* but *won't*.

---

## Rules of Engagement (92-94)

A Muslim must **never** kill another Muslim intentionally. If it happens by accident, there are rules: free a believing slave (if applicable) and pay blood money to the victim's family.

And a crucial rule for the battlefield:

> *"O you who believe, when you go out in the cause of God, investigate, and do not say to one who offers you peace: 'You are not a believer,' seeking the gains of worldly life."* (94)

If someone on the battlefield says they're Muslim or offers peace, **accept it**. Don't kill them and claim they were lying just to take their possessions. The benefit of the doubt goes to the person claiming peace.
